"{\"uid\": \"balkaninsight.com-2024-02-08-winter-glory-sarajevans-bittersweet-memories-of-the-1984-olympics-btj\", \"text\": \"This post is also available in this language:ShqipBos/Hrv/Srp  Four decades ago, 1,510 athletes from 49 different countries were congregating in Sarajevo, the capital of Bosnia and Herzegovina, which at the time was part of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, and was hosting the 14th Winter Olympic Games.  But it looked like the competitors had a big problem - there was no snow. Only a day before the official opening of the games, grass was still visible at the tournament sites and the temperate weather was showing no signs that it might change.  \\\"Everybody is happy,\\\" Pavle Lukac, an official from the Sarajevo '84 organising committee,told theNew York Timestwo days before the games. \\\"We are waiting for snow, but we do not want to decorate the city with it until after all the planes have landed.\\\"  But on the night of February 7, 1984, the weather changed drastically and snow covered the mountains, giving the organisers another headache - would they be able to clear it all in time for the Games' opening ceremony?  The snow needed to be removed from the roads towards the sites, the competition tracks and courses, and from the seats at the Kosevo Olympic Stadium, where the opening ceremony was going to be held the following day. High school students were drafted in to help clear it.  The opening ceremony on February 8, 1984. Photo \\u00a9 1984 Comit\\u00e9 International Olympique (CIO).  Munevera Begic, now 79, said she remembers that night \\\"like it was yesterday\\\".  \\\"I remember that we were all on the edge as there was the possibility of cancelling the Games, as there was no snow,\\\" Begic told BIRN at her home in Sarajevo.  \\\"But when the first snowflakes showed up, hopes rose, and as soon as it turned into a blizzard, it felt like a countrywide festival,\\\" she said.  When daytime came on February 8, 1984, the roads were clean, the arenas ready, and the Kosevo Olympic Stadium filled up with visitors for the opening ceremony. In the stadium, at 2.30pm exactly, fanfares blared out to mark the beginning of the ceremony. The Olympic torch was lit by a sporting representative of Yugoslavia, skater Sanda Dubravcic, who came from what is now independent Croatia.  The Olympic torch is lit by Sandra Dubravcic at the opening ceremony on February 8, 1984. Photo: \\u00a9 1984 Comit\\u00e9 International Olympique (CIO).  Around the world, approximately 2.5 billion viewers tuned in to watch the Sarajevo '84 Games from February 8 until February 19. A total of 222 medals were awarded to 2,691 athletes and coaches. Ticket sales soared to 640,000, while the event received extensive coverage from 7,825 journalists representing 760 media outlets.  At the time, East Germany (with nine gold, nine silver, and six bronze medals) and the USSR (with six gold, ten silver, and nine bronze medals) emerged as the most successful competing nations. But the home country, Yugoslavia, would also have a story to tell about its own medal-winning hero.  A couple kisses on the bobsleigh track used at the 1984 Winter Olympic Games at Mount Trebevic near Sarajevo.\\u00a0 Photo:EPA-EFE/FEHIM DEMIR.  When Yugoslavia was chosen to host the 1984 Winter Olympic Games at venues up on the mountains around Sarajevo, expectations were high.  Yugoslavs were ecstatic and were keen to get their country ready to shine. The infrastructure for the competition was built in fewer than six years, quicker than any other Olympic construction work had been completed before.  \\\"Companies from all around Yugoslavia participated in the construction, my late husband worked in a company in Cacak [in Serbia] and they worked on the construction of the bobsled track on Trebevic mountain,\\\" Begic said.  The Winter Olympics incurred a total expenditure of $141,647,000 but concluded with a $12,000,000 surplus, making it the first Olympics to end up with money left over. The surplus was used to build facilities in other cities, which are still in use as events venues today, like Dom Mladih in Sarajevo and the Mejdan hall in Tuzla.  The Mojmilo Olympic Village construction site in Sarajevo. Photo: \\u00a9 1984 Comit\\u00e9 International Olympique (CIO).  Previous Olympics had ended with financial deficits, posing significant difficulties for the host cities. But Yugoslavia was able to raise extra funding from an apparently willing source: the general public.  \\\"Each of us participated in the construction via donations from each paycheck,\\\" Begic said, adding that \\\"it was the law and nobody had anything against it\\\".  Under Yugoslav law, every citizen had to contribute to infrastructure projects for the common good.\\u00a0There were 1,200,000 individual donations\\u00a0and more than 4,000 group donations from companies.  \\\"I remember kids coming from all around the country for rehearsal days before the opening. They all lived together at the time, and my late daughter was one of them,\\\" Begic remembered. Young participants from all over Yugoslavia were billeted in student dormitories in the Bosnian capital while they worked on the routines for the opening ceremony.  \\\"She was ecstatic for months after the games finished,\\\" Begic added.  But just a few years later, Begic lost her daughter in the war that erupted as Yugoslavia collapsed.  Pedestrians on the streets of Sarajevo under a poster of Vucko. Photo: \\u00a9 1984 Comit\\u00e9 International Olympique (CIO).  Yugoslavia had an extensive network of public broadcasting services in each of the six federal republics. During the games, a TV station from each country was given the task of covering one field of competition.  But in the run-up to the games, the public broadcasting network was used to appeal to Yugoslav artists to participate in a competition to create the mascot for the games.  Joze Trobec, a painter, caricaturist and designer from Slovenia, was among those who noticed the competition call back in 1981.  \\\"When I saw that announcement, at first I did not decide; then, at home, I drew some very stylised animals,\\\" Trobec told BIRN. \\\"Then I decided to participate in the competition,\\\".  Vucko, mascot of the 1984 Winter Olympic Games, painted on the bobsleigh track at Mount Trebevic near Sarajevo, January 2024. Photo: EPA-EFE/FEHIM DEMIR.  He noted that many previous Olympic Games had cartoon animals for mascots. Moscow 1980 had Misha the Bear, while Montreal 1976 had Amik the Beaver.  \\\"Then I started thinking about what would be good, what would symbolise both the sporting games and perhaps Sarajevo, and perhaps Bosnia,\\\" Trobec said.  \\\"And I remembered that as a boy I read some stories about wolves, about Bosnia, about [Mount] Jahorina, so the idea came to me that maybe a wolf would be good to make as a mascot,\\\" he added.  The smiling mascot was named Vucko - Wolfie or Little Wolf. Back in February 1984, theNew York Timesmused that \\\"the cheerful, wolfish face of the Olympic mascot, Vucko\\u2026 may leave its own legacy\\\" in Bosnia and Herzegovina.  Forty years later, pictures of the cartoon animal can still be seen on posters on the walls of restaurants and cafes around the Sarajevo area, as well as on souvenirs and even in graffiti.  In today's divided society, Vucko is \\\"the only thing that all Bosnians can agree on\\\", said Trobec.  Jure Franko (2nd), Max Julen from Switzerland (1st) 1st and Andreas Wenzel from Liechtenstein (3rd) after the giant slalom event. Photo: \\u00a9 1984 Comit\\u00e9 International Olympique (CIO).  Sarajevo '84 distinguished itself in various ways. It was the first modern Olympics unmarred by Cold War boycotts by either NATO or Warsaw Pact countries and boasted the highest-ever participation in terms of nations sending competitors.  But it also marked the year in which Yugoslavia secured its inaugural Winter Olympic Games medal. In a tense race, Slovenian skier Jure Franko clinched the silver medal in the giant slalom event, making the dreams of many Yugoslavs come true.  \\\"For days, everyone talked about it,\\\" Begic remembered. \\\"Sarajevans even had a saying which goes, 'We love Jurek more than burek [traditional Balkan pie],'\\\" she added.  But after the initial part of the race, Franko's victory was far from assured as he found himself in fourth position.  But during the latter stages, the skier delivered the fastest time, propelling himself into second place. His achievement marked a historic milestone for Yugoslav winter sports.  \\\"I started skiing at three years old,\\\"Franko saidat a news conference after the medal-giving ceremony. \\\"I must thank my father at home, who is no doubt very happy. He is the one who put me on skis.\\\"  But Franko senior was not the only one happy - the rest of Yugoslavia was too.  \\\"There was no kid who did not know who Jure Franko was in the years after the games,\\\" Begic said.  Ski jump platforms on Mount Igman near Sarajevo. Photo: \\u00a9 1984 Comit\\u00e9 International Olympique (CIO).  As Yugoslavia celebrated Franko's silver medal, few could have imagined that the country was only a few years from collapse, and that before too long, it would cease to exist completely.  In 1984, the Games were seen as a triumph for Sarajevo, Bosnia and Yugoslavia.  \\\"The whole city breathed with both heart and soul to make that event as successful as possible,\\\" Ahmed Karabegovic, the secretary-general of the Sarajevo '84 organising committee,saiddecades later.  \\\"And we also wanted to present Sarajevo as a city of peace, love, friendship, sport, and all the positivity that Olympianism carries within itself,\\\" Karabegovic added.  A lot of the infrastructural legacy of the Games was ruined by the 1992-95 war, when Sarajevo was under siege for three-and-a-half years. The ski resorts on Mount Bjelasnica and Mount Jahorina are still fully functioning, however, while the Olympic Village in Sarajevo's Mojmilo neighbourhood has been turned into a residential complex.  Apart from that, there is only the ageless face of Vucko and the memories of people like Begic and Trobec, who still speak of the old times with a feeling of sentimentality and regret.  \\\"We were all proud of Sarajevo and of Yugoslavia,\\\" said Begic. \\\"This, today, this is not even close to the life we had.\\\"    This post is also available in this language:ShqipBos/Hrv/Srp  Copyright BIRN 2015 |Terms of use|Privacy Policy  To provide the best experiences, we and our partners use technologies like cookies to store and/or access device information. Consenting to these technologies will allow us and our partners to process personal data such as browsing behavior or unique IDs on this site and show (non-) personalized ads. Not consenting or withdrawing consent, may adversely affect certain features and functions.  Click below to consent to the above or make granular choices.\\u00a0Your choices will be applied to this site only.\\u00a0You can change your settings at any time, including withdrawing your consent, by using the toggles on the Cookie Policy, or by clicking on the manage consent button at the bottom of the screen.      \"}"